# Macronutrients

#### Nitrogen
- Part of all living cells
	- Proteins, enzymes, transfer of energy
	- Chlorophyll
- Helps plants with rapid growth
	- increasing seed and fruit production
	- Improving leaf quality
- Primary nutrient needed in soil amendment
	- Often the *only* one needed, because it dissapates fast
- Caveats
	- Drains from soil very rapidly, so it needs frequent amendment
- Sources
	- Fertilizer application
	- Small amounts from rain
	- Highly water-soluble
	- Nitrogenous compost, or nitrogen-rich compost components
		-

### Things that can't be composted

</div></div>

	- Plants can take up multiple forms of nitrogen
		- Atmospheric
			- N2
			- CANNOT be used by plants
		- Nitrate
			- NO3-
			- Negative charge
			- Most used by plants
			- Most easily lost to groundwater
		- Ammonium
			- NH4+
			- Positive charge
			- AKA Amonium Nitrogen
			- Used directly in proteins
			- Not lost as easily
		- Organic Nitrogen
			- c-NH2
				- Where c is a complex organic group
				- Generally have no charge
				- IE Urea, 2(NH2)CO
					- Produced by all animals
					- Odorless
					- When dissolved, neither acidic or alkaline
					- Bacteria convert urea to ammonium
						- And ammonium to nitrate
							- Releases H+ ions, acidifies
						- Converted quickly, <2 days
						- Urea and ammonium are collectively referred to as "ammoniacal nitrogen"
					- Used by the body in nitrogen excretion (?)
					- Widely used in fertilizers
					- Must go on ground. not foliage
						- Away from the stems, where root hairs are
					- ![Pasted image 20220928134953.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
			- Changed into ammonium, then into nitrates, by microbes
				- Can be directly used by the plant
			- Coffee grounds
				- Has to be cold
				- Neutral pH
				- Cold tea works too
		- Commercial formulas combine all 3
			- IE Ammonium nitrate
				- Most common by far (99%)
				- It's a salt, which kills microbes
				- Also explosive
- Sources
	- Atmosphere
	- Biological and atmospheric fixation
	- Precipitation
	- Industrial fixation
	- Animal manures
		- Bird manure contains urea because they piss/shit at the same time through their cloaca
- Deficiency
	- Causes leaves to be wimpy, yellow
	- Starts at low, old leaves, and moves upwards towards new growth
	- ![Pasted image 20220928134702.png](data:image/png;base64,)
- Nitrogen excess
	- Damages tips of leaves
- Inhibits root development
	- Urine diluted 10:1, emergency nitrogen
		- Must be fresh
		- Medications come out in urine

## Micronutrients and mineral nutrition
- Any of these can become toxic if there is too much
	- ALWAYS test wellwater before using
		- Can remove with double-filtration, but very expensive
	- Come as anions or cations
		- Anions
			- Bind to soil, best in acidic conditions
		- Cations
			- Can be leached

## Soil mixes
- Main nutrients
	- N
		- Used for growth in all phases
		- inhibits root development
		- sources
			- miracle gro
		- Lost much faster than other nutrients
			- Chemically unstable
		- High nitrogen low others results in wimpy stems
			- Calcium helps
			- So does bud pruning/pinching, makes plant wider
	- K
		- works with calcium and magnesium to manage turgor pressure
		- Needed in all phases of growth
	- P
		- good for flowers and fruits
		- good for root development
		- sources
			- kelp / seaweed meal
	- Micronutrients
		- Magnesium
		- Calcium
		- Sulfur
		- Iron
		- Manganese
		- Zinc
		- Copper
	- Mictobiota and rhizal fungi
